error.signature: ValueError: not enough values to unpack (expected 2, got 1)
error.regex: ValueError: not enough values to unpack \(expected \d+, got \d+\)

verdict.summary: Tuple unpacking mismatch. Common in for loops over dicts without .items().

dead_ends.why_fails: Masks the real issue — wrong data shape

dead_ends.action: Pad the iterable with None values
dead_ends.why_fails: Doesn't fix the source of wrong-length data

workarounds.action: Check if iterating dict — use .items() for key-value pairs
workarounds.how: for key, value in my_dict.items():  # not: for k, v in my_dict:

workarounds.action: Print/inspect the actual data to see its shape, then fix unpacking count
workarounds.how:
for line in data:
    parts = line.split(',')
    print(f'Expected 3 fields, got {len(parts)}: {parts}')
    # Now fix unpacking count to match actual data shape

frequently_confused_with.distinction: 'ValueError' is a value_error error while 'ValueError' has a different failure mode despite similar symptoms. Check error message details to differentiate.
